occurrences.line_text: And of his wonder made religion,
And made ech member quake, and manly hart to quayle.
That sudden newes had made into his spright;
Where goodly solace was vnto them made,
In all which time, Sir Artegall made way
This dismall day hath thee a caytiue made,
And made him oft, when he would strike, forbeare;
And sad melancholy: there he his cabin made.
His doole he made, there chaunst a turtle Doue
Which losse her made like passion also proue.
And thereof made a lamentable lay,
As if she would haue made him vnderstand,
Ne then of guile had made experiment,
Then beautie, which was made to represent
And made the baite of bestiall delight:
Was made the vassall of the victors might;
That her deare hart full deepely made to rew,
And made it so to ride, as it aliue was found.
And made his Dwarfe, though with vnwilling ayd,
She had them made a paragone to be,
Vpon all which the Briton Prince made seasure,
Her tender heart, and made refraine from meat,
Till he had made of her some better priefe,
All which by nature made did nature selfe amaze.
So all the world by thee at first was made,
That in her cheekes made roses oft appeare:
Should for the Gods in Proteus house be made;
That made the rockes to roare, as they were rent.
And made it seeme to feele her grieuous paine,
That made him stoupe, till he did him bestride:
And chyde at him, that made her misbelieue:
Made humble suit vnto his Maiestie,
He graunted it: and streight his warrant made,
For of most perfect metall it was made,
His name was Talus, made of yron mould,
And made them stoupe, that looked earst so hie.
And made way for his maister to assaile.
They turne to that, whereof they first were made?
That he of little things made reckoning light,
Where he her spous'd, and made his ioyous bride.
But like as one, whom feends had made affrayd,
And what a glorious shew he made in all their sights.
And made the scorne of Knighthod this same day.
And made her famous, more then is belieued;
They pressed forward, entraunce to haue made.
It made her stagger oft, and stare with ghastly eye.
Made them all enter in before her sight,
Whose other wing, now made vnmeete for flight,
In stead whereof she made him to be dight
And wyder made the wound of th'hidden dart.
With which the Gods themselues are mylder made:
Who will not stoupe with good, shall be made stoupe with harme.
How earnest suit she earst for him had made
Ne would abide, till she had aunswere made,
Now ye haue made my heart to wake alway,
His wife was Isis, whom they likewise made
And clothed all in garments made of line,
Vnto the bone, and made a griesly wound,
What May-game hath misfortune made of you?
And magistrates of all that city made,
Made them sweare fealty to Artegall.
Against him made againe. So both anon
Amends may for the trespasse soone be made,
Till he himselfe was made their greedie pray,
Or made them both one masse withouten more remorse.
And made a griesly wound in his enriuen side.
That made him raue, like to a Lyon wood,
And made him backe againe as fast to fly;
Made of straunge stuffe, but all to worne and ragged,
With peremptorie powre, that made all mute;
Being then new made widow (as befell)
Raced, and made smooth fields now full of flowres?
And in her necke a Castle huge had made,
And made it beare the yoke of inquisition,
That made him stagger with vncertaine sway,
Most richly made, but there no Monster did behold.
Made kill her selfe for very hearts despight,
That made him stagger, and stand halfe agast
And for her entrailes made an open way,
And made him oftentimes in field before me fall.
Made cruell hauocke of the baser crew,
Made him become most faithlesse and vnsound:
And made to fly, like doues, whom the Eagle doth affray.
That many wounds into his flesh it made,
Did much the more augment, and made most vgly cases.
Of all on earth, and made a matchlesse paragon.
That oft he made him stagger as vnstayd,
And made such piteous mourning therewithall,
That made him stoupe to ground with meeke humilitie.
So suffring him to rise, he made him sweare
Where goodly glee and feast to them she made,
That through the mayles had made so strong a breach
There him he causd to kneele, and made to sweare
How great a hazard she at earst had made
He was invulnerable made by Magicke leare.
Yet in his bodie made no wound nor bloud appeare.
And by rude tokens made to her appeare
He made great mone after his saluage mood:
Which earst he left, he signes vnto them made,
Recured well, and made him whole againe:
Into his gaping throte, that made him grone
Made in his tender flesh, but whole them all he found.
That made them grow so high t'all honorable hap.
She made him thinke it surely was his owne,
Yet he them all withstood, and often made relent.
That made him downe vnto the earth encline;
Made in the bodies of that Squire and Dame;
Made all of rusty yron, ranckling sore,
Mylde answer made; he was an errant Knight,
That made him euermore increase his speedie pace.
With which he layd about, and made them fast to flie.
The warrant straight was made, and therewithall
Then vp he made him rise, and forward fare,
That slaine he was, or made a wretched thrall,
They made amongst them selues; but when her face
Whereat they shouted all, and made a loud alarme.
And made the wood to tremble at the noyce:
Ensewing, made her knowen to him at last:
That made him scoule, and pout, and oft complaine
When the bold Centaures made that bloudy fray
That made him pipe so merrily, as neuer none.
Vnto thy loue, that made thee low to lout;
And made great mone for that vnhappy turne.
She made me often pipe and now to pipe apace.
To future age of her this mention may be made.
That to thy blisse I made this luckelesse breach,
But fed on spoile and booty, which they made
Now made the spoile of theeues and Brigants bad,
For vnderneath the ground their way was made,
And pittifull complaints, which there she made,
So from thenceforth, when loue he to her made,
And made vnfit to serue his lawlesse mindes behest.
Made answere, that the Mayd of whom they spake,
But he, that in his mind had closely made
Whereof right glad they seem'd, and offer made
Through the dead carcases he made his way;
That long had lyen dead, and made againe aliue.
That made him almost mad for fell despight.
Of surest yron, made with many a lincke;
That madest many Ladies deare lament
His mightie hands did on the madman lay,
Madman (said then the Palmer) that does seeke
Madnesse to saue a part, and lose the whole.
And in his madnesse thinke with hands impure
Deepe Indus, and Maeander intricate,
First entering, the dreadfull Mage there found
He doubted, least it were some magicall
Thither the great Magicien Merlin came,
His Magick bookes and artes of sundry kindes,
Which still she bore, replete with magick artes;
Then Elfinor, who was in Magick skild;
Mo[N]Gst thousand dangers, & ten thousand magick mights.
For pleasing words are like to Magick art,
Which Bladud made by Magick art of yore,
The hidden power of herbes, and might of Magicke spell?
My bodie all, through charmes and magicke might,
In charmes and magicke to haue wondrous might,
As when her face is staynd with magicke arts constraint.
No magicke arts hereof had any might,
All liuing wightes in might of magicke spell:
Ybuilded all of glasse, by Magicke powre,
May learned be by cyphers, or by Magicke might.
For Merlin had in Magicke more insight,
In vaine seekes wonders out of Magicke spell.
By strong enchauntments and blacke Magicke leare,
Thereto she learned was in Magicke leare,
He was invulnerable made by Magicke leare.
Of Magistrates, of courts, of tribunals,
And magistrates of all that city made,
The great Magitian Merlin had deuiz'd,
But read (said Glauce) thou Magitian
So wedded th'one to Maglan king of Scots,
In whose dead face he red great magnanimity.
What huge heroicke magnanimity
Of mightie Magnes stone, whose craggie clift
As th'Idole of her makers great magnificence.
With stately port and proud magnificence,
And with magnificke might and wondrous wit
Magnificke Virgin, that in queint disguise
Whose porch, that most magnificke did appeare,
And would as Ammons sonne be magnifide,
Was neuer king more highly magnifide,
That art in mighty armes most magnifide
To heare her Loue so highly magnifide,
Of whom ye seeke to be most magnifide:
His famous conquests highly magnifide:
The which through fame should farre be magnifide,
To magnifie his owne. But when they heard,
And all faire Ladies magnifie your might,
And much did magnifie his noble name.
Yet she her selfe the more doth magnify,
And magnifying louers deare debate;
And oftentimes by Turmagant and Mahound swore.
And fowly said, By Mahoune, cursed thiefe,
And vow by Mahoune that he should be slaine.
Like to the rod which Maias sonne doth wield,
When tidings came to me vnhappy maid,
With chaunge of cheare the seeming simple maid
Who now is left to keepe the forlorne maid
Me silly maid away with him he bare,
Glad of such lucke, the luckelesse lucky maid,
How with that pensiue Maid he best might thence arise.
Then hunt the steps of pure vnspotted Maid:
How shamefully that Maid he did torment.
Shapt like a maid, that such ye may her know;
Shew'dst thou, then in this royall Maid of yore,
The warlike Maid, th'ensample of that might,
Then the braue Maid, which all this while was plast,
What shall of me vnhappy maid become?
A wofull wretched maid, of God and man forgot.
Was for the loue of that same snowy maid,
Till Scudamour, and that same Briton maide,
In that late Turney for the snowy maide;
Aye me to see that gentle maide so tost.
There did the warlike Maide her selfe repose,
Too much am I to blame for that faire Maide,
The pitteous maiden carefull comfortlesse,
The forlorne Maiden, whom your eyes haue seene
Did seeme such, as she was, a goodly maiden Queene.
The Maide[n]; proud through prayse, and mad through loue
A seemely Maiden, sitting by the shore,
But greatest shame was to that maiden twin,
The prayse of her fresh flowring Maidenhead;
Vnto the noble Knights of Maidenhead,
But still the Knights of Maidenhead the better wonne.
All the braue Knights, that hold of Maidenhead,
And knights of Maidenhead, whose praise she would empaire.
Of knights, addrest his maiden-headed shield,
That noble order hight of Maidenhed,
Nor halfe so fast to saue her maidenhed,
The wanton Maidens him espying, stood
An hundred naked maidens lilly white,
Forgo that royall maides bequeathed care,
With th'Heliconian maides for maistery;
And counseld with her Nourse, her Maides attire
To be this maides, with whom I fastned hand,
So cruell doale amongst her maides dauide,
Her warlike maides about her flockt so fast,
Into the which hereafter thou maiest happen fall.
To proue the wide report of her great Maiestee.
Beares he himselfe with portly maiestee,
To see him in his soueraigne maiestee,
Mirrour of grace and Maiestie diuine,
With royall pomp and Princely maiestie;
Present before the maiestie diuine,
Adornes the person of her Maiestie;
For with dredd Maiestie, and awfull ire,
The wise Elficleos in great Maiestie,
And vse of awfull Maiestie remoue:
Tempred with sternesse and stout maiestie,
Made humble suit vnto his Maiestie,
Therefore I humbly craue your Maiestie,
A Princesse of great powre and maiestie,
Thus she did sit in souerayne Maiestie,
Who bowing low before her Maiestie,
Yet tempred with some maiestie imperiall.
Bate somewhat of that Maiestie and awe,
Who streight her leading with meete maiestie
Singing before th'eternall maiesty,
Of royall maiesty and soueraigne name;
With goodly arras of great maiesty,
Sitting like King of fowles in maiesty and powre.
And in her soueraine Maiesty to sit,
Great Gloriana, greatest Maiesty,
And her endowd with royall maiestye:
A stately siege of soueraigne maiestye;
In wouen maile all armed warily,
That with their force they perst both plate and maile,
To measure manhood by the sword or maile.
And shields did share, & mailes did rash, and helmes did hew.
And mailes betweene, and laced close afore:
And lightly leaping from so monstrous maine,
He smot thereat with all his might and maine,
Vere the maine shete, and beare vp with the land,
Who shall him rew, that swimming in the maine,
For with such puissaunce and impetuous maine
The walles so stoutly with their sturdie maine,
Yet life he saw, and felt his mightie maine,
Suddeine they see from midst of all the Maine,
Fierce battell against one, with cruell might and maine.
His deawy head out of the Ocean maine,
And droue at him with all his might and maine
In minde to leape into the mighty maine,
That all the countrey seemes to be a Maine,
Through her maine strength, in which she most doth trust,
Long so she on the mightie maine did flote,
His bowre is in the bottome of the maine,
In deawy vapours of the westerne maine,
Of all the heard, meete with so hideous maine,
And ran at him with all his might and maine;
He smote at him with all his might and maine,
And oft to grone with billowes beating from the maine.
I will thrust downe into the deepest maine,
They both together ioyned might and maine,
Gan driue at him, with so huge might and maine,
Amid their shields, with so huge might and maine,
So well was tempred, that for all his maine,
He did him smite with all his might and maine,
His stroke redoubled with such might and maine,
But hayld and puld with all his might and maine,
Vpon them two they fell with might and maine,
Like as the wounded Whale to shore flies fro[m] the maine.
Where he him fou[n]d despoyling all with maine & might.
The land to sea, and sea to maineland dry,
That now no more we can the maine-land see,
Mainly they all attonce vpon him laid,
But strikes his sayles, and vereth his mainsheat,
Arise, and with like treason now maintain
And drew his deadly weapon, to maintain his part.
Or else his wrong with greater puissance maintaine.
Throughout the world her mercy to maintaine,
Or ought that else your honour might maintaine,
Their stedfast stonds did mightily maintaine,
His glory did repose, and credit did maintaine.
That none against them battell durst maintaine.
Thereto him Ate stird, new discord to maintaine.
And vow'd with speare and shield it to maintaine;
By all meanes to maintaine that castels ancient rights.
And to maintaine, that she all others did excell.
But either others cause to maintaine mutually.
Of knights and armed men, which did maintaine
This euill manner, which ye here maintaine,
Which tooke in hand her quarrell to maintaine;
Ripe yeares of reason, my right to maintaine.
Maintaine this euill vse, thy foes thereby to foile.
A wrongfull quarrell to maintaine by fight;
For greater force there needs to maintaine wrong, then right.
By Arthure, when as Vnas Knight he did maintaine.
Euen seuen hundred Princes, which maintaynd
Might be maintaynd, and each gan diuersely deuize.
And all such persons, as did late maintayne
Because he had not well mainteind his right,
Had lodging in so meane a maintenaunce,
That may not be (said he) ne maist thou yit
In this faire mirrhour maist behold thy face,
Long maist thou liue, and better thriue withall,
There thou maist loue, and dearely loued bee,
There maist thou best be seene, and best maist see:
There maist thou best be seene, and best maist see:
For dead, I surely doubt, thou maist aread
Came to their wicked maister, and gan tell
O how can beautie maister the most strong,
Vnto his maister, he no lenger would
That his owne sire and maister of his guise
And stroue to maister sorrowfull assay,
Haue made you maister of the field this day,
Your fortune maister eke with gouerning,
And maister these mishaps with patient might;
There by his maister left, when late he far'd
The maister Cooke was cald Concoction,
Vnto their maister, who in bed was layd,
Had it purloyned for his maister bad:)
With that, the wicked carle the maister Smith
To guide the beast, that did his maister beare,
And made way for his maister to assaile.
And for to maister wrong and puissant pride,
Ne will enforced be with maisterdome or might.
That him so noble knight had maistered,
Life hauing maistered her sencelesse foe;
Her plong, as ouer maistered by might,
His cursed hand withheld, and maistered his might.
Ne may loue be compeld by maisterie;
For soone as maisterie comes, sweet loue anone
And Guyon in them all shewes goodly maisteries.
To practise games, and maisteries to try,
Bridling his will, and maistering his might:
His siluer shield, now idle maisterlesse;
The wofull Dwarfe, which saw his maisters fall,
The maisters of his long experiment,
The maisters of her art: there was she faine
But Trompart, that his maisters humor knew,
Thy maisters shame, in harlots bondage tide.
Had from their maisters fled, & now sought hyre elswhere.
With th'Heliconian maides for maistery;
That fierce young mans vnruly maistery;
Mishaps are maistred by aduice discrete,
That Monster can be maistred or destroyd:
Yet with strong reason maistred passion fraile,
Great maistresse of her art was that false Dame,
Whom when his maistresse proud perceiu'd to fall,
When with the maistring spur he did him roughly stire.
And maistring might on enimy dismayd:
Who maistring them, renewd his former heat;
The maistring raines out of her weary wrest,
As her slow beast could make; but all in vaine:
Yet rests not so, but other meanes doth make,
As euer Proteus to himselfe could make:
To bring forth fruit, and make eternall derth,
Goe guiltie ghost, to him my message make,
And by my ruines thinkes to make them great:
To make one great by others losse, is bad excheat.
And damned sprights sent forth to make ill men aghast.
Where none appeares can make her selfe a way:
Of whom he meanes his bloudie feast to make,
And eke wyld roring Buls he would him make
(A lesson hard) and make the Libbard sterne
And for to make his powre approued more,
And ioyd to make proofe of her crueltie
Vpstarted lightly from his looser make,
But vanquisht thine eternall bondslaue make,
And was possessed of his new found make.
Then for to make her dreaded more of men,
He has them now foure yeres besiegd to make the[m] thrall.
The righteous man, to make him daily fall?
Her hastie ruine does more heauie make,
That with your worth the world amazed make,
Could make a stony hart his hap to rew;
Ensample make of him your haplesse ioy,
And eke from whom make ye this hasty flight:
For what hath life, that may it loued make,
All which, and thousands mo do make a loathsome life.
Should make his marke, high heauen to attaine?
Their heauenly notes, and make full many a louely lay.
That shall ye euermore renowmed make,
And boystrous battell make, each other to auenge.
That deeper dint therein it would not make;
Where falling flat, great humblesse he did make,
The tydings straunge did him abashed make,
Here she a while may make her safe abode,
And great atchieu'ments great your selfe to make,
But now, faire Ladie, comfort to you make,
Or make you good amendment for the same:
Then Guyon forward gan his voyage make,
And of your ignorance great maruell make,
Whom raging windes threatning to make the pray
She scorning both their spights, does make wide way,
Of her lewd parts to make companion;
An yearely solemne feast she wontes to make
When of his pitteous tale he end did make;
Of his reuenge to make the instrument:
And wondred in his mind, what mote that monster make.
A siluer sound, that heauenly musicke seemd to make.
With her two crooked handes she signes did make,
Which mariage make; that day too farre did seeme:
Strong warres they make, and cruell battry bend
That matter make for him to worke vpon,
Should him dismay, and make him stoup so low,
Was wonne: So matter did she make of nought,
Can chaunge my cheare, or make me euer mourne;
There her small Gondelay her port did make,
How they themselues doe thine ensample make,
Wilfully make thy selfe a wretched thrall,
In his owne flesh, and make way to the liuing spright.
The priuate state, and make the life vnsweet:
Thy spouse I will her make, if that thou lust,
And make his carkasse as the outcast dong?
Coulin to make, being eight lugs of grownd;
Did head against them make, and strong munificence.
Where he an end of battell, and of life did make.
A downe the streame, and all his vowes make vaine,
Through hils and dales he speedie way did make,
So end of that Carles dayes, and his owne paines did make.
So riu'd her trembling hart, and wicked end did make.
Did afterwards make shipwracke violent,
Great whirlpooles, which all fishes make to flee,
Did wisely make, and good Agdistes call:
To make there lenger soiourne and abode;
To make more triall of his hardiment,
With whom he meant to make his sport & courtly play.
Some to make loue, some to make meriment,
Some to make loue, some to make meriment,
And striuing, fit to make, I feare do marre:
Thy selfe thy prayses tell, and make them knowen farre.
To speake a while, ne ready answere make,
And also it impregnable did make;
Till death make one end of my dayes and miserie.
Or why make ye such Monster of your mind?
To make his wonne, low vnderneath the ground,
Both Sunne and Moone, and make them him obay:
But of their first intent gan make new dout
Or what needs her to toyle, sith fates can make
Thou then shalt make, t'increase thy louers pray.
Of secret foes, that him shall make in mischiefe fall.
Ouer the troubled South, that it shall make
But the third time shall faire accordaunce make:
Him shall he make his fatall Instrument,
Will not long misery late mercy make,
That it shall make him shake, and shortly learne to fall.
Ye see that good king Vther now doth make
Will bring, and shortly make you a mayd Martiall.
Therefore faire Infant her ensample make
Sir knight, that doest thy voyage rashly make
And doth for wretched mens reliefe make way;
To make ensample of his heauenly grace,
So all did make in her a perfect complement.
The whiles the ioyous birdes make their pastime
And mortall miseries doth make her play.
Would make to melt, or pitteously appall;
To make exceeding mone, as they had bene vndonne.
Whom she did meane to make the thrall of her desire.
She turnd, and semblaunce of faire fight did make;
And seeing none in place, he gan to make
A daughter of the Titans which did make
To make another like the former Dame,
He gan make gentle purpose to his Dame,
Then he would make himselfe a mortall wight;
So thinking for to make her stubborne courage quaile.
And threatned there to make her his eternall thrall.
By such close signes they secret way did make
To milk their gotes, and make them cheese and bred,
